Losing Face: Racial Bias in Biometric Recognition Technology

When Robert Williams was taken into custody this past January, little did he know what would be in store for him. At the time, the Detroit police department was actively looking into a robbery at a Shinola retail store. After nearly three months of inconclusive investigation, the Michigan state police took over and decided to pull a security video of the incident. The individual appearing in the grainy footage was run against facial recognition software from a company called DataWorks. A match came back for Williams who was immediately arrested and detained for 30 hours. However, charges were dropped after officers eventually acknowledged that “the computer must have been wrong.” But significant harm was done. What happened to Williams that day went down as the first wrongful arrest in the U.S. due to facial recognition mismatch.
